description._value: Metabolic response of copepods from the genus Calanus exposed to CO2 concentrations of 380ppm (ambient) and 1000ppm at 8°C and 10°C in the absence of food over a period of 5 days. The responses of all low molecular weight, polar and non-polar metabolites were quantified using direct infusion mass spectrometry and multivariate statistical analyses.

Metabolites were extracted from each sample, using a two-step methanol/ water/chloroform protocol. In brief, 100 µl methanol (HPLC grade) and 40 µl water per copepod were added to each sample prior to homogenization using a Precellys-24 ceramic bead-based homogenizer (Stretton Scientific, UK). Thereafter, 50 µl water and 100 µl chloroform per copepod were added to each sample, which was vortexed and centrifuged (1800 rcf, 10 min, 4 ºC), yielding an upper (polar) and lower (non-polar) fraction for each sample. Each polar fraction was collected into a 1.5 ml Eppendorf tube, and the non-polar fraction into a 1.8 ml glass vial. Extraction blanks were also prepared using identical methods except that no biological material was added to the solvents. Two quality control samples were pooled from polar and nonpolar extracts, respectively. All polar samples were dried in a centrifugal concentrator (Thermo Savant, Holbrook, NY), the nonpolar samples under a stream of nitrogen gas. All samples were stored at -80 ºC prior to analysis.

Direct infusion mass spectrometry data acquisition in the positive ion mode was performed on a LTQ-FT Ultra mass spectrometer (Thermo Fisher Scientific, Bremen, Germany) with a chip-based Advion Triversa direct infusion nanoelectrospray source (Triversa, Advion Biosciences, Ithaca, NY).  The polar extracts designated for this ion mode were each taken up in 100 µl of 0.25 % formic acid in methanol / water 4:1. Samples were centrifuged (10 min, 22000 rcf, 4℃) to remove any particular matter. They were run in a controlled-randomized sequence different from the extraction sequence, in three technical replicates which followed each other immediately. QC samples were run in the beginning, the end, and equidistantly throughout the sequence. Data was acquired at nominal 1E5 resolution from m/z 70-590, in 7 wide SIM (selected ion monitoring) windows. Nonpolar (lipid) samples were taken up in the original volume of methanol / chloroform 3:1, containing 5 % ammonium acetate. Data were acquired in increasing SIM windows of 100 Da to 200 Da width, from m/z 120 to 1200.
Raw mass spectral data were processed using the SIM-stitching algorithm (scripts available on request), using an in-house Matlab script.

The data matrices were normalized using the PQN algorithm. Missing values were imputed into the resulting data matrix using the KNN algorithm via an in-house R script. This matrix would be used for univariate statistics.
The matrix was transformed using the generalised logarithm to stabilise the variance across the measured peaks prior to analysis with multivariate statistics.

title._value: The metabolomic response of marine copepods to environmental warming, ocean acidification and food deprivation
